summary: Since 2011, annual glacial lake outburst floods (GLOFs) from Suicide Basin above the Mendenhall Glacier have ranged from minor, largely unnoticed events to nuisance flooding that affected roads and campgrounds with minimal damage. On August 5, 2023, an unprecedented flood caused the Mendenhall River to surge to ~15 feet, sweeping a home away and condemning several others, followed by an even more extreme event on August 6, 2024, that crested at 16 feet and inundated nearly 300 properties, triggering emergency evacuations. These escalating floods highlight the increasing risks to the Mendenhall Valley as glacier retreat and unstable meltwater buildup intensify over time.

floodhistory: Near annual event. Release Frequency: 1-3 years between Aug-Dec.
summary: The Snow Glacier Dammed Lake is located in the headwaters of the Snow River east of Moose Pass and is blocked by the Snow Glacier. The lake drains subglacially. When the lake releases, it causes a notable rise on Kenai Lake and the upper Kenai River. The volume of this lake has averaged 90,000 to 140,000 Acre-feet over the past 30 years. The lake typically releases every two to three years in the fall; however, has the potential for an annual release.

floodhistory: Have been observed since 1967. Events are uncommon.
